2026-04-21 01:29:42 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Input Cable (+) connection inside control module', 'Series path through control-module switch and associated PCB trace / wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurement shows the power‑supply module delivers ~12 V between its two output cables. At the control module, however, both outgoing cables to the load sit at 0 V relative to PSU negative, meaning the + rail from the PSU never reaches the control module output pair.\n\nContinuity test with power off indicated:\n- An open circuit between Control Input Cable (+) and Control Output Cable (+) even with the switch closed.\n- A low-resistance connection (0.10 Ω) between Control Input Cable (−) and Control Output Cable (−).\n\nThis proves that the negative line is correctly passed through the control module, but the positive line is broken somewhere inside the control module along the intended + path (from the incoming + cable, through the switch and its wiring/PCB trace, to the outgoing + cable). Because the red inverted‑cables indicator LED is off, the + and − lines are not swapped; they are simply interrupted on the + side.\n\nThe most probable root cause is a fault in the internal + path of the control module: e.g. a loose or unsoldered joint at the Control Input Cable (+) lug, a broken PCB trace to/from the switch, or a defective switch contact.\n\nRepair should focus on restoring continuity from the Control Input Cable (+) to the Control Output Cable (+) through the switch path inside the control module.'
